From: gt8134b@prism.gatech.EDU (Howlin' Bob)
Crossposted-To: comp.os.ms-windows.advocacy
Subject: Re: NT versus Linux, the updated and expanded comparison chart, version 2
Date: 22 Aug 93 22:26:27 GMT

kevin@frobozz.sccsi.com (Kevin Brown) writes:

>true dynamic link
>libraries (DLL)             yes                         yes (shared)
>per-application DLLs        yes                         yes, but unnecessary
>                                                       due to paging.

It should be pointed out that multiple invocations of the same executable,
such as the shell, share all text pages and clean data not only with each
other, but with the buffer cache.   This makes for fast loading ane
very low memory consumption.

>runs DOS apps               yes                         some, via emulator

Both use an "emulator," which is in actuality just a DOS box.  Windows NT
on an i386 platform uses virtual-8086 mode, just as Linux dosemu does.
NT on a non-i386 platform uses a software 8086 emulator, which is slow.
But on i386 platforms, the NT and Linux approaches are fundamentally 
identical.

>kernel max addressable mem  2048 Gig                    4 Gig

This simply cannot be if we are talking about the same architecture.
The 80386/80486 only supports 4 GB of physical memory.  The current
Linux memory management scheme gives the kernel a 1GB address space,
making only 1 Gb of physical memory usable.  I don't think that's
too limiting; it could be changed if necessary.

>proc max addressable mem    4 Gig (???)                        4 Gig

Nope.  I don't know NT's, but Linux's is 3 GB.  This is, again, a side
effect of Linux's clean and simple memory management scheme; the kernel
and user memory spaces reside in the same page tables, making accessing
user space from kernel space a simple matter of "segmentation" (NOTE!
the user space is still "flat.")  Again, if the need were great, the
mm could be restructured to give 4 Gb to the process and 4 GB to the
kernel.  It just doesn't seem necessary. 

>- I don't think the Linux kernel is set up to address more than 4 gig
>  internally.  You'd have to play with segment registers to access more
>  than that.  Not that it matters at this point.  By the time you have

Worse: you simply cannot address more than 4 GB physical mem at all on
an 80386, and there's no need to have the kernel addressing virtual memory
(well, there is, but it isn't worth the trouble to have a pageable kernel).
All the segmentation in the world won't help.

>- Linux wasn't designed at the outset to port to every piece of hardware
>  available.  If you want that attribute, then perhaps this comparison should 
>  be between BSD and NT.  That Linux is being ported to the 680x0 is evidence 
>  enough that it's at least somewhat portable.

The 680x0 effort, as I understand, is trying to keep the 68k and i386 
architecture-specific code in separate trees.  If so, these changes could
be merged back into Linus' Linux, making it truly portable.  NetBSD has
a head start on this, however.

>- Alan Cox reports that his March beta of NT had unstable networking.  I
>  don't know if it's been fixed.  So I've marked it as tentatively stable
>  until I find out otherwise (thus giving NT the benefit of the doubt).

Even so, NT networking might not buy you anything.  NFS comes with Linux
networking: does it come with NT?

>  windowing), then I don't see what the big hubbub about networking in NT
>  is all about.  NFS, FTP, telnet, etc., are all nice and everything, but
>  it's old technology.  So's client/server windowing, for that matter, but

Excuse me?  Networked filesystems are extremely important, as are remote
procedure calls.


--
