From: gt8134b@prism.gatech.EDU (Howlin' Bob)
Subject: Re: NT versus Linux, the updated and expanded co
Date: 22 Aug 93 22:30:52 GMT

imcclogh@cs.ucsd.edu (Ian McCloghrie) writes:

>cflatter@nrao.edu (Chris Flatters) writes:

>>Again, I believe this is a little unfair.  A 486 is recommended for W/NT
>>but it should run on a 386 or 386sx.

>       I was told, when I expressed interest in seeing how well (poorly?)
>NT would run on my 10M 386DX/25 that it made use of the 3 or 4 instructions
>that exist in the 486 and not in the 386.  (mostly to do with clearing
>the on-chip cache, etc).  Is this true?

Everyone seems to focus on the few instructions that the 486 has but
the 386 doesn't.  Well, BSWAP is a nice one for networking on our
wrong-ended machines, but there is a more important consideration:
the 486 can make write-protect applicable even in privilege ring 0.
I imagine these two are the reason that NextSTEP, for example, claims
that it needs a 486.

Linux is full of verify_area() calls tomake sure the kernel doesn't
write into the wrong places.  I'd like to see the x86 variable in
the kernel, which holds a 3 for 386, 4 for 486, 5 for Pentium, actually
be used for something.  Enabling the correct 486 write-protect handling
and short-circuiting all those verify_area() calls would be nice.

--
Robert Sanders
Georgia Institute of Technology, Atlanta Georgia, 30332
